      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my dissertation and i keep hitting a wall with my p-values. if i get a p-value of 0.06, why is it technically \"not significant\" even if the effect size looks pretty big? it feels like the math is ignoring the trend.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your p-value of 0.06 is considered \"not significant\" because it exceeds the conventional threshold, typically $\\alpha=0.05$. This means there's a 6% chance of observing your data, or something more extreme, if there were actually no true effect in the population. While a large effect size suggests a strong trend, the p-value is sensitive to sample size and variability, which is why it can sometimes overshadow a seemingly strong directional effect. It's important to consider effect sizes and confidence intervals alongside your p-value to get a complete picture of your results.",
      "source": "target",
