    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if the noise is systematic like you said, that's even more annoying. it's like there's this hidden factor that's constantly messing with the data points. is there any way to model that kind of unpredictable interference, or do you just have to accept that it's there and ruins the statistical power of the study?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you suspect a hidden systemic factor, the most robust approach is to incorporate it into your model using more complex regression techniques, such as adding interaction terms or using mixed-effects models. Mixed-effects modeling, in particular, allows you to account for nested data structures or time-dependent effects that might be acting as this unobserved interference. Instead of accepting the noise, you are essentially modeling it to isolate the variance explained by your primary variable of interest.",
      "source": "target",
